				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/29/business/29bits-airbnb/29bits-airbnb-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/29/business/29bits-airbnb/29bits-airbnb-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/29/business/29bits-airbnb/29bits-airbnb-blog480.jpg" id="100000002850953" width="480" height="320" alt="Regulation is a direct challenge to Airbnb&#039;s business model and that huge public offering expected later this year."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Regulation is a direct challenge to Airbnb's business model and that huge public offering expected later this year.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Justin Sullivan/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A few weeks ago, the renegade Nevada cattle rancher Cliven Bundy became famous for challenging the authority of the federal Bureau of Land Management. He promptly drew many supporters, both on the ground and in the conservative media, before he derailed his cause with racist comments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">InÂ a milder but similarÂ vein, Airbnb, the incredibly successful home rental service, is increasingly drawing a lineÂ in the sandÂ withÂ New York regulators <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/22/business/companies-built-on-sharing-balk-when-it-comes-to-regulators.html?_r=0">who want to exercise oversight</a> on its business. Airbnb says, in essence, that it does not recognize their authority. And it is doing all it can to rally supporters to its cause.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A petition chastising Eric T. Schneiderman, the New York attorney general, was unveiled over the weekend. By late Monday, it was <a href="https://campaigns.peers.org/petitions/new-york-attorney-general-schneiderman-protect-all-of-us?af=1977852&amp;utm_source=airbnb&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=NYC_petition_Guests_042614&amp;c=144395#   ">closing in on 25,000 signatures</a>. The petition aims to put pressure on Mr. Schneiderman, who i<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/technology/albany-judge-hears-case-against-airbnb.html">s battling Airbnb in court</a> for the names ofÂ 15,000 hosts in the city and other related data.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">AirbnbÂ called his effort an overbroad and inappropriate requestÂ andÂ accused theÂ attorney generalÂ of harassing New Yorkers who are just trying to get by. Mr. Schneiderman, who said he was willing to narrow his request, believes most of the New York listings on the site are illegal short-term rentals. New York law prohibits just about all apartment rentals of less than 30 days. (Selling rooms or aÂ night on a couch is permitted.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The petition conjures up a vision of Airbnb as a sort of public advocate for a group on the verge of eviction. &#8220;For many of us, Airbnb is the only thing that keeps us in the homes we love,&#8221; it says.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Left unmentioned is the fact that Airbnb is valued at $10 billion, more than the Hyatt Hotels Corporation. The petitionÂ is onÂ Peers.org, an advocacy group whose close ties to Airbnb were described<a href="//www.fastcompany.com/3022974/tech-forecast/is-peers-the-sharing-economys-future-or-just-a-great-silicon-valley-pr-stunt"> in a Fast Company article</a>. &#8220;Businesses can be part of social change, just like nonprofits,&#8221; Natalie Foster, Peers&#8217; executive director, told the magazine.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The petition begins with this sentence: &#8220;Attorney General Schneiderman, youâve said you are fighting for the big hotels, but as attorney general, itâs your job to protect all New Yorkers.&#8221; The part about the big hotels came from <a href="//nypost.com/2014/04/24/ny-ag-slams-airbnb-vows-to-protect-hotel-industry/">a New York Post story</a> last week, where Mr. Schneiderman was quoted as saying at an eliteÂ event that he would &#8220;protect the state&#8217;s &#8216;extraordinarily successful&#8217; hotel industry.&#8217; &#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A transcript provided by Mr. Schneiderman&#8217;s office showed that his apparently full-throated defense of hotelsÂ reads somewhat differently in context.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">First he said that &#8220;we have a well-regulated and extraordinarily successful hotel sector&#8221; that is &#8220;one of our finest industries and contributes a lot to the economy.&#8221; Then, a bit later, he added, &#8220;We&#8217;re just looking in New York to enforce New York law, and also, frankly, to protect our hospitality industry that goes through a lot of trouble to have great hotels, to protect tourists, to provide services, and to protect the people in our residential housing.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He seemed to be saying that there was a reason for regulation, which is what you would expect a regulator to say. It did not seem to be a confession that he was a tool of the hotel industry, which is what The Post and the petition imply.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An Airbnb spokesman said he did not think the quote was taken out of context.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The petition was started by Evelyn Badia, a freelance producer of TV commercials. In an interview, she said she was not one of the shady entrepreneurs running illegal hotels that the attorney general says are widespread. She needs her two Airbnb properties â in her Brooklyn house she has a private apartment as well as a room she rents outÂ â to keep afloat. &#8220;In 2011, I worked 20 days,&#8221; she said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Badia is an eloquent if unpaid advocate for Airbnb and the sharing economy.Â Her suspicion of the attorney general seemed genuine. &#8220;He&#8217;s asking for a lot of data,&#8221; she said. &#8220;He says he&#8217;s not targeting me today. How do I know he&#8217;s not going to target me two years down the line? My place is legal today, but what about tomorrow?&#8221; She added, &#8220;I came here from Puerto Rico as a child, so whenever you start throwing the &#8216;legal&#8217; word at me, I go a little crazy.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And yet she said she also seesÂ Mr. Schneiderman&#8217;sÂ point. &#8220;I used to live in a co-op apartment,&#8221; she said. &#8220;If someone in the building was constantly renting out his place on Airbnb, I don&#8217;t think I would have liked it. This is not a black-and-white issue.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Airbnb is trying to brand Mr. Schneiderman a bad guy, a sort of urban Bureau of Land Management. It wants Airbnb hosts to be accountable to the Airbnb community, not regulators. Regulation is a direct challenge to its business model and that huge public offering expected later this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In San Francisco, there is no figure like Mr. Schneiderman to attack, <a href="//www.sfgate.com/realestate/article/Petition-to-alter-S-F-laws-for-Airbnb-rentals-5414140.php">so a petition this month </a>merely called for an overhaul of laws that prohibit short-term rentals. It garnered more than 25,000 signatures. The president of the city Board of Supervisors has now introduced legislation to essentially make Airbnb legal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But nothing is a sure thing. Airbnb sent out a message to its users on Monday saying, &#8220;We&#8217;ve just been informed of a ballot initiative that will be introduced tomorrow that would severely limit â and possibly end â short-term rentals in San Francisco.&#8221; It is calling for a Tuesday rally at City Hall.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 05/05/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">6</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Airbnb Rallies Supporters.</p>    </div>
